Thank you for all who joined us for today’s IG Live where @ihadamiscarriage and I spoke openly about the various components of grief and loss.

Our conversation included: 

*Jessica’s personal experience with pregnancy loss.

*How to support someone who has experienced loss.

*Ways to access support for grief.

*The importance of normalizing the grieving process.

Thank you @ihadamiscarriage for being so courageously open and transparent about your healing journey.

Today I had the opportunity to speak about panic attacks with @anxietyjosh, a UK psychotherapist and author.

Our conversation included:
*What are panic attacks?
*The physiological and psychological components of panic attacks. 
*The effectiveness of graded exposure.
*How to shift from avoidance and fear to curiosity and understanding.

Thank you so much for all who joined us and contributed to this fruitful conversation! 

#anxiety #panicattack #mentalhealth

For Day #15 of the December Mental Health Instagram Live Series I got to speak with @refugeingrief about the topic of grief.

Our conversation included:

*Societal ideas about grief
*What does “being stuck” in grief mean.
*The importance of understanding the language we use around grief.
*Ways to normalize grief:

Thank you all who joined us today and each day of this wonderful month dedicated to mental health awareness!

#grief #griefjourney #loss

#trauma #healing #traumainformed

For Day #8 of the December Mental Health Instagram Live Series I had the opportunity to speak with Eric @samehere_global about our shared advocacy work to change the conversation around mental health.

Our conversation included: 
*Why the current 1 in 5 statistic divides 
*How emotional & mental health education is currently being implemented in schools
*New ways to raise awareness 
*How to start shifting the conversation from illness to normalizing the fact that we all struggle.

Thank you for everyone who joined and helped facilitate this great conversation!

#samehere #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealth

node.text:
We live in a society that commonly applauds and encourages us to distance ourselves from unhealthy romantic relationships.

But what about all the other dynamics and relationships in our lives that no longer serve us?

The unhealthy family dynamic.

The toxic or abusive work environment.

The one-sided friendship.

The scale.

The people pleaser inside of us. 

A midweek reminder that we are allowed to step away and break up with anything that is harmful to our mental health.

What other areas in our life can we give ourselves permission to break up with?

node.text:
When addressing our physical health, we do not wait to treat an injury or condition until it reaches a critical state or stage 4.

We act on the onset of physical symptoms, providing relief with the hope of reversing the negative impact.

It’s so important to address our mental health needs in the same manner.

We must not wait until we are in crisis or our symptoms become severe.

We need to treat mental health concerns on the ONSET, when symptoms first emerge.

A friendly reminder that you don’t need to be at your lowest to get help.

May be an image of text that says 'Dr. Christina @DrChistina There is preventative care for our physical health (annual checkups lab work, medical screenings, shots). There is preventative care for our dental health (professional cleanings, X-rays, routine dental examinations). So where is the preventative care for our mental health?'.

node.text:
If you want me to get all kinds of hot and bothered, invite me to a conversation about our current mental healthcare system.

Our insurance panels will cover and approve all sorts of preventative measures to ensure our physical health stays intact, everything from annual checkups to routine lab work to flu shots.

Our dental insurance will cover professional cleanings, dental examinations and routine X-rays.

So where is our preventative care for mental health?

Where is our quarterly mental health checkups with a therapist to screen for mental health challenges?

It doesn’t exist and instead mental health care is much more crisis management than anything else.

This NEEDS to change.

We need access to PREVENTATIVE resources such as education, early intervention screenings, access to mental health care and supportive services that do not require a severity threshold to be met.

Preventative mental health care is the health care we need.

And we need it now. 💚

node.text:
When I lose 10 lbs then I won’t struggle with my body image.

But then I lose the 10 lbs and I still struggle. 

When I get this promotion then I will feel worthy of finding a partner.

But then I get the promotion and I still feel unworthy of love. 

When I receive forgiveness from those around me then I can forgive myself.

But I receive their forgiveness and I still can’t let go of my shame and guilt. 

It doesn’t matter how many times we try to change the outside in an effort to fix the inside, we will always fall short for they are simply temporary solutions.

We have to truly dig deeper and openly explore the parts of ourselves that are in pain.

Only then can we heal and have freedom from our pain. 💚

node.text:
Follow enough therapists on social media and you are bound to come across a post or two about the importance of “feeling your feelings.”

The sentiment behind this statement highlights the importance of actively feeling our emotions versus suppressing or avoiding the difficult ones.

I 100% stand behind the benefit of feeling our feelings as they arise, seeing them as informed messengers.

With that being said, it’s also equally important to state that we don’t need to feel all of our feelings all the time.

Sometimes too many feelings show up and processing each one would overwhelm our nervous systems.

Sometimes the feelings are too heavy to continue to carry for such long periods of time.

Allow this to be a gentle reminder that while feeling our feelings are absolutely important, so is allowing yourself space, respite and distance from them. 💚

node.text:
In the height of my panic attacks, I was a teenager living a life dictated by fear.

I was around 16-years-old when I started to feel like my world was closing in.

I became fearful of everything, even things that once brought me joy like traveling and spontaneous adventures.

I remember telling my therapist that I wouldn’t leave my safe zone (aka a 25 mile radius) until “my anxiety was better.”

She looked at me with gentle eyes yet a firm tone and said, “Sometimes the fear doesn’t go away. Sometimes you have to do things scared.”

Initially I didn’t listen as my anxiety was much louder than her words encouragement. 

But little by little I began to do things scared.

A short trip on public transit to a place I hadn’t been.

A medium flight to a location that once brought me joy. 

A long train ride along the country side. 

All in an attempt to intentionally combat my anxious thoughts. 

Each time I stretched my comfort zone my anxiety tried to tell me I wouldn’t be able to do it, that my panic attacks would only stay away if I was in a safe and familiar place.

And each time I did it scared, my anxiety got a little quieter.

A gentle reminder that sometimes the fear doesn’t go away.

Sometimes we have to do things scared.

node.text:
I have lots and lots of feelings about trauma.

The majority of my clinical work revolves around supporting those who have been most traumatized.

From working in the ER as a sexual assault response team member to providing therapy for foster youth, I have seen varying degrees of the trauma experience.

And I am here to say that being forced to witness, experience or survive trauma doesn’t mean there is anything “wrong” with you.

You are not flawed, damaged or undeserving.

What is wrong is the fact that you were exposed and experienced traumatic events. 

A gentle reminder that if you have experienced trauma, you are not and never were the problem. 💚
